      <p>
      The tower is the most fully-realized example of Japanese Metabolism, an
      architectural style that seems born out of the population explosion and rapid
      densification of post-war Tokyo. The idea was to build massive towers on
      floating platforms over water to expand Japan's usable acreage. The
      Capsule Tower is made of modular concrete pods (capsules) that are bolted onto
      two central towers. Theoretically a capsule could be moved or replaced as
      needed.
      </p>

      <p>
      Unfortunately the building fell into disrepair, for why I can't find good
      reason, but I'll guess that this idealistic, cramped, view of urbanization
      started to look pessimistic to the public over the years.
      </p>

    </div>
